Today I want to show you the way we make things in the future.
I believe that soon our buildings and machines will be self-assembling, self-replicating, and self-healing.
So I'm going to show you what I think the current state of manufacturing is, and then compare it to some natural systems.
Then in current manufacturing, we have skyscrapers - two and a half years, 500,000 to a million parts, very complex, using new technologies in steel, concrete and glass.
We have exciting machines that can take us into space - five years and two and a half million parts.
But on the other hand, if you look at natural systems, we have two million types of proteins that can fold in 10,000 nanoseconds, and we can replicate DNA with three billion base pairs in about an hour.
That's the complexity of our natural systems, but they're very efficient, more efficient than anything we've built, more complex than anything we can build.
They are more efficient in terms of energy.
They rarely make mistakes.
They can self-repair to maintain longevity.
There's something super interesting about natural systems.
If we can translate that to our built environment, there's a lot of potential in the way we build things.
I think the key is self-assembly.
If we want to use self-assembly in our own physical environment, I think there are four key factors.
The first is that we need to decode all the complexity of what we want to build - that is, our buildings and machines.
We need to decode them into simple sequences - basically the DNA of how our buildings work.
Then we need a programmable part that can accept this sequence and be used for folding or reshaping.
We need some energy for activation, so that these parts of us can fold according to the program.
We need some type of error-correcting redundancy to ensure that what we successfully build is what we want.
So I want to show you some of the projects that my colleagues and I are working on to make this self-assembling future a reality.
The first two projects are MacroBot and DeciBot.
These projects are large-scale reconfigurable robots - 8-foot, 12-foot-long proteins.
They are embedded in electromechanical devices, sensors.
You need to decode the way you want to fold it, decode it into a series of angles - negative 120 degrees, negative 120 degrees, 0 degrees, 0 degrees, 120 degrees, negative 120 degrees, - that sort of thing; a series of angles, or turns, and you can transmit that order by wire.
Each cell gets its own message - say, negative 120. It rotates, checks if the rotation is in place and then passes the sequence to its neighbor.
There are many brilliant scientists, engineers and designers working on this project.
I think this project really reveals: Is this really scalable?
I mean, it took thousands of dollars and many man hours to build this eight-foot robot.
Can we really expand it? Can we really embed robots in every part?
The next question is to look at passivity, or passively trying to make restructuring programmable.
But it goes a step further. It tries to do the actual calculations.
It basically embeds the basic building block of most computing, the digital logic gate, directly into the various parts.
This is the wrong door.
Each gate to be used for calculation has a tetrahedron on it, with two input tetrahedrons.
One is the input from the user, like you're building bricks.
The other is the input of a brick that was placed before coming.
It then gives the output of the three-dimensional space.
This means that users stack bricks in the way they want.
It calculates based on what has been done before and your instructions.
Now it begins to move in three dimensions - up or down.
Look at the left side, the input of [1,1] is equal to 0 output, which means down.
On the right, the input of [0,0] is 1 output, indicating up.
So what this really means is that our structure now contains the blueprint of what we want to build.
So the information about what you want to build is all embedded.
This means that we have a form of self-replication.
In this case, I call it self-directed replication, because your structure contains the exact blueprint.
If you encounter an error, you can replace a part.
All the local information is embedded in it, telling you how to fix it.
So you have something that can climb, that can read it and output it one by one.
It is directly embedded; there is no external command input.
The last item I'm going to show is called the eccentric chain, and it's probably the most exciting example of a passive self-assembly system that we're seeing right now.
It is reconfigurable and programmable, making it a completely passive system.
Basically, you have a series of elements.
Each element is exactly the same, and they are eccentric.
Each chain, or each element wants to turn right or left.
If you're going to assemble a chain, you need to program it.
Tell each unit whether to turn left or right.
When you shake the chain, it folds up and programs whatever structure you've coded for it - so in this case, a helix, and in the case of fire, two connected cubes.
Basically you can program in three dimensions - or one dimension, two dimensions - and the chain is completely passive.
