Recently, we have seen the impact of cyber attacks on the business world.
Data breaches at companies like JPMorgan Chase, Yahoo, Home Depot and Target have resulted in hundreds of millions, if not billions, of dollars in losses.
A few more such attacks, and the entire world economy would collapse.
The public sphere is not immune.
From 2012 to 2014, the U.S. Office of Personnel Management had a very serious data breach.
Security clearance and fingerprint information was stolen, affecting 22 million employees.
You may have also heard that some government-sponsored hackers are trying to use stolen data to influence the outcome of elections in some countries.
The two most recent were the massive theft of data from the German Bundestag and the theft of emails from the US Democratic National Committee.
Cyber threats are already affecting our democratic processes.
And there is a growing trend.
The more advanced the computer technology, the more vulnerable the means we use to protect our data.
In particular, a new computer technology, called a quantum computer, uses microscopic particles in nature to greatly increase the computing power of computers.
Its computing power is powerful enough to break many of the encryption systems we use today.
So are we hopeless?
Should we start packing up our electronic survival gear for the coming data apocalypse?
I don't think we're there yet.
Quantum computers exist only in laboratories and are still years away from practical use.
More importantly, there have been many major breakthroughs in the field of encryption.
To me, this is a very exciting time in the history of secure communications.
About 15 years ago, I learned that we had unlocked new skills to create quantum effects that do not exist in nature. I was very excited.
The idea of using the fundamental laws of physics to advance cryptography is thrilling to me.
Today, a select group of companies and labs, including mine, have advanced this technology to the point of practical application.
That's right.
We intend to fight quantum with quantum.
How can this be achieved?
First, let's take a quick look at the world of encryption.
You need a briefcase, and you have some important documents to give to your good friend, James Bond, to lock up and keep safe.
Because this material is top secret, we're going to use a super advanced briefcase.
It comes with a special combination lock that, once locked, turns the contents of the file into random numbers.
So you just put the file in, lock it, and by this time the file has been converted to a random number, and you give the briefcase to James.
When the briefcase hasn't arrived, you call him and tell him the password.
Once he gets the briefcase, enters the code, and the document is deciphered, it's perfect. You've successfully passed an encrypted message to James Bond.
(Laughter) A funny example, but it illustrates three important points about encryption.
The password - we call it the encryption key.
You can think of it like a password.
The phone call that gave James the password.
We call it key passing.
This ensures that we can safely deliver the secret key to the designated location.
And the lock used to encrypt and decrypt files.
We call it an encryption algorithm.
Through the secret key, it converts the contents of the file into random numbers.
A good algorithm can do this, and it is difficult to crack the password without the secret key.
The importance of the algorithm is that if someone gets the briefcase and opens it, without the secret key, without knowing the encryption algorithm, they can't read the contents of the document.
All you get is some random numbers.
Most security systems rely on secure key delivery, where the key is delivered to the right place.
However, the rapid increase in computing power has jeopardized many of the key transfer methods we currently use.
To take one example, we now have a very widely used system - RSA.
When it was invented in 1977, it took about 4 quadrillion years to crack a 426-bit RSA key.
By 1994, just 17 years later, the code had been cracked.
As computers get more powerful, we need longer and longer passwords.
Now we often use 2048 or 4096-bit passwords.
As you can see, the battle is on between the encryptors and the decryptors, each trying to outdo the other.
In the next 10 to 15 years, the arrival of quantum computers will make it faster to crack the complex mathematical algorithms that are the basis of the encryption systems we use today.
In fact, quantum computers will turn our castle of security into a house of cards that collapses at a touch.
We have to try to protect our castle.
In recent years, many research institutions have emerged to study how quantum effects can be used to enhance encryption.
There have been some exciting breakthroughs.
Remember the three keys to encryption? High-quality keys, secure key delivery, and strong algorithms.
Advances in science and engineering, however, have jeopardized two of these priorities.
First and foremost is the secret key.
Random numbers form the basis of the secret key.
But today, they are no longer truly random.
At present, we generate secret keys, which are generated by software based on random number frequencies, which we call pseudo-random numbers.
Numbers generated by programs or mathematical methods will always have some, perhaps not so obvious, regularities in them.
The less random these numbers are, or, in the jargon, the lower the power they contain, the easier they are to predict.
Recently, some casinos have been attacked in a very creative way.
They focused on the slot machine for a while, and then analyzed.
Cybercriminals used reverse engineering to create the pseudo-random number generator behind the turntable.
In this way, they have a great chance to predict the rotation of the turntable, and thus earn a lot of money.
The secret key is equally insecure.
Having a truly random number generator is important for generating secure passwords.
For years, researchers have been trying to create a truly random number generator.
But most designs are either not random enough, not fast enough, or hard to reuse.
But the quantum world is truly random.
It's important to take advantage of this true randomness.
Devices that can measure quantum effects can generate a continuous stream of random numbers very quickly.
The casino crime just mentioned can no longer be staged.
Several universities and companies from around the world are concentrating on making truly random number generators.
In my company, our quantum random number generator is born from an optical table that is 2 meters long and 1 meter wide.
Then we shrunk it down to the size of a box.
Today, it can be loaded onto a PCI card and plugged into an ordinary computer.
This is the world's fastest, truly random number generator.
By measuring quantum effects, it can generate 1 billion random numbers per second.
Today it is widely used around the world to enhance the security of cloud service providers, banks and government agencies.
(Applause) But even with true random number generators, we face a second major cybersecurity threat: the secure transmission of secret keys.
Current key-transfer technology is no match for quantum computers.
The quantum solution to this problem, called quantum key distribution, or QKD for short, takes advantage of a fundamental counterintuitive property of quantum mechanics.
Observing the behavior of a microscopic particle changes the particle.
Let me give you an example.
Come to think of it, give the code to James Bond.
But this time, instead of calling him, we used quantum effects to carry the code with a laser beam and transmit it to James through an ordinary optical fiber.
Let's assume that Dr. No wants the password.
Fortunately, Dr. No's attempts to intercept the quantum key will leave electronic fingerprints that James and you will be able to detect.
In this way, the intercepted key is invalidated.
And the secret key left behind can provide strong protection for the data.
Because this security mechanism is based on fundamental principles of physics, it is impossible for a quantum computer, or any future supercomputer, to crack it.
My team and I are working with a number of leading universities and the defence sector to refine this exciting technology and develop the next generation of security products.
